How to use the ETL Validation Prompt Generator
Part 1 — Fill in the generator
Step 1 — SIT Databricks connection
Enter your SIT Databricks workspace details:

Workspace URL — copy it from your browser when logged into the SIT Databricks workspace (e.g. https://adb-1234567890.azuredatabricks.net)
Cluster ID — go to Compute → click your SIT cluster → copy the Cluster ID from the configuration tab
HTTP path — go to Compute → your cluster → Advanced Options → JDBC/ODBC tab → copy the HTTP path
Auth method — choose one:

Personal Access Token → go to your SIT workspace → top-right avatar → User Settings → Access Tokens → Generate New Token → paste it in
Service Principal → ask your Azure admin for the Tenant ID, Client ID, and Client Secret of the registered app
Env Variable → set DATABRICKS_HOST and DATABRICKS_TOKEN as environment variables on your machine before running


Catalog — the Unity Catalog name in SIT (e.g. sit_catalog). Find it in Data Explorer in your workspace
Default schema — the schema where your raw/curated tables live (e.g. bronze, silver)

Step 2 — Add your delta table pairs

Click "Add table pair" for each table you want to validate
Enter the full 3-part path: catalog.schema.table_name for both the raw and curated versions
Example: sit_catalog.bronze.orders → sit_catalog.silver.orders

Step 3 — Select validation checks
Toggle the checks you want to run. Recommended minimum set: Structure, Row Count, Data, Duplicates, Hash.
Step 4 — Select load strategies
Pick only the strategies that apply to your pipeline. For example, if your pipeline uses CDC, select CDC. Selecting irrelevant strategies will add unnecessary validation steps.
Step 5 — Outlook email settings

Choose your send method:

win32com — simplest option if you're on Windows with Outlook installed
Graph API — best for running in Databricks jobs/pipelines without a desktop
SMTP — works for any Exchange/Office 365 setup


Optionally pre-fill a default email — the script will suggest it at runtime but the user can override it

Step 6 — Report settings

Give the report a meaningful title
Enter your primary key columns (comma-separated, e.g. id, customer_id)
Enter a partition or watermark column if using incremental/CDC strategies (e.g. load_date)

Step 7 — Generate
Click "Generate validation prompt", then either Copy the prompt or click "Send prompt to Claude ↗" to run it directly.

Part 2 — Running the generated code
Prerequisites — install these packages first:
pip install databricks-connect databricks-sql-connector pywin32 msal requests
For Databricks notebooks, most of these are pre-installed. Only install what your chosen auth/email method needs.
Step 1 — Run the script
Paste the generated code into either:

A Databricks notebook in your SIT workspace (recommended — Spark is already available)
A local Python script on a Windows machine with Outlook installed (for win32com method)

Step 2 — Enter your email when prompted
The very first thing the script does is ask:
Enter recipient email for the validation report: _
Type your email and press Enter. It will validate the format and re-ask if invalid. In a Databricks notebook, a widget appears at the top of the notebook instead.
Step 3 — Wait for validation to complete
The script will:

Connect to SIT Databricks and verify the connection
Load each table pair as Delta DataFrames
Run all selected validation checks (structure, count, duplicates, hash, etc.)
Run load strategy validations
Compile everything into an HTML report

Step 4 — Receive the email
Once complete, the HTML report is automatically sent to your email via Outlook. Check your inbox for the subject line:
ETL Validation Report — SIT — 2026-05-06 14:32
The email body contains the full interactive HTML report. The .html file is also attached as a backup.

